revision.text:
The '''Aconcagua mummy''' is an Incan ''[[capacocha]]'' mummy of a seven-year-old boy, dated to around 500 [[Before Present|BP]].{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}} The mummy is well-preserved, due to the extreme cold and dry conditions of its high altitude burial location.{{sfn|Wade|2015}} The frozen mummy was discovered by hikers in 1985 at {{convert|5300|m|abbr = on}} on [[Aconcagua]] in [[Mendoza, Argentina]].{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}}{{sfn|Wade|2015}}

==Discovery==
The Aconcagua mummy was buried inside a semicircular stone structure{{sfn|Ceruti|2015}} and found covered in vomit, red pigment, and fecal remains.{{sfn|Faux|2012}} The body was wrapped in textiles in a style derived from central coastal Peru.{{sfn|Cassman|2007|p=144}} Six statuettes were also found buried with the body.{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}}

An analysis shows that the boy's diet consisted primarily of maize, quinoa, capsicum, potatoes, and terrestrial meat. A year and a half before his death, his diet became more marine-based.{{sfn|Faux|2012}} The presence of [[achiote]] was also found inside his stomach and colon.{{sfn|Cassman|2007|p=144}}

==Archaeogenetics==
In 2015, DNA was extracted from a {{convert|350|mg|abbr = on}} sample from one of his lungs.{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}} His mtDNA lineage belongs to a subgroup of [[Haplogroup C (mtDNA)|Haplogroup C1b]], the previously unidentified C1bi (''i'' for Inca).{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}} His mtDNA lineage contains 10 distinct mutations from C1b.{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}} The researchers determined that Haplogroup C1bi likely arose around 14,300 years ago.{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}} An individual from the [[Wari Empire]] was found to be a match for this previously unidentified haplogroup.{{sfn|Gómez-Carballa|Catelli|2015}}{{sfn|Wade|2015}} In 2018, researchers sequenced the [[genome]] of the Aconcagua mummy from a {{convert|100|mg|abbr = on}} sample from one of his lungs.{{sfn|Moreno-Mayar|Vinner|de Barros Damgaard|de la Fuente|2018|p=12 (Supplementary)}} His Y-DNA lineage belongs to [[Haplogroup Q-M3]].{{sfn|Salas|Catelli|Pardo-Seco|Gómez-Carballa|2018}} His specific Y-DNA haplogroup is closest matched by the Choppca people from [[Huancavelica]], a [[Quechua people|Quechua speaking population]], and clusters closer to modern Quechua speaking peoples than [[Aymara people|Aymara speaking peoples]].{{sfn|Salas|Catelli|Pardo-Seco|Gómez-Carballa|2018}} Overall, the genome of the Aconcagua mummy clusters with modern Andean populations.{{sfn|Moreno-Mayar|Vinner|de Barros Damgaard|de la Fuente|2018|p=21 (Supplementary)}}

