w of the Tinbergen Building, named after [[Nikolaas Tinbergen]]]]
The '''Department of Zoology''' is the [[zoology]] department of the [[University of Oxford]], England, which is part of the university's [[Mathematical, Physical and Life Sciences Division, University of Oxford|Mathematical, Physical and Life Sciences Division]].
==Overview== The department has several institutes and a Research Unit in and around the [[Radcliffe Observatory Quarter]], [[Science Area, Oxford|Science Area]] and [[Oxford]]:<ref name="oxford15">{{cite book| title=Oxford University Pocket Diary | year=2014–15 | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | chapter=Zoology, Dept of | page=175 }}</ref>
* [[Biodiversity Institute]] * [[Edward Grey Institute of Field Ornithology]] * [[Institute for Emerging Infections]] * [[Wildlife Conservation Research Unit]] (WildCRU – in [[Tubney]], [[Oxfordshire]])
Research in the Department focuses on the themes of [[Animal behaviour|behaviour]], [[disease]], [[ecology]], and [[evolution]]. The Department is within the Mathematical, Physical and Life Sciences Division of Oxford University. The main building, the [[Tinbergen Building]] (named after [[Niko Tinbergen]]), is on the corner of [[South Parks Road]] and [[St Cross Road]], with [[Linacre College, Oxford|Linacre College]] and an entrance to the [[University Parks]] opposite.
In February 2017, officials announced that the Tinbergen Building would be closed for two years and all research and teaching activities of the Zoology Department would be moved elsewhere in the university due to the discovery of [[asbestos]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15084594.Oxford_University_to_close_buildings_and_relocate_hundreds_of_staff_after_asbestos_discovery/ | title=Oxford University Zoology and experimental psychology buildings to close for two years due to asbestos | newspaper=[[Oxford Mail]] | accessdate=11 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-38934959 | title=Asbestos find closes Oxford University building for two years | publisher=[[BBC]] | work=[[BBC News]] | date=10 February 2017 | accessdate=1 May 2017 }}</ref>
